# CVE-2026-27601 (underscore.js DoS) is no longer suppressed here: it is
# now actually fixed in the image. The vulnerable 1.13.7 copy is a static
# JS asset vendored by the base image's legacy nbclassic package; the
# Dockerfile now patches it in place to the upstream-fixed underscore 1.13.8
# (see the nbclassic note there). nbclassic itself is kept — the rise-classic
# UI (the featured Quantum Coin Game) depends on it — so removal was not an
# option. A suppression here would not help downstream consumers anyway: a
# repo-level .trivyignore does not propagate to images that re-scan the
# published artifact (e.g. traQmania's release gate), so the fix has to live
# in the image. With the asset genuinely at 1.13.8, this entry is redundant;
# keeping it out means CI re-blocks if the patch ever regresses.

# CVE-2026-25087 - apache-arrow C++ use-after-free DoS in pyarrow.
#
# Fixed in pyarrow 23.0.1. We cannot reach it: pyarrow is pulled in only
# transitively, and qiskit-serverless (in every -xl/-xxl flavor) hard-caps
# pyarrow<22 — true even of the latest serverless 0.32.0 (pyarrow<22,>=21).
# serverless itself is locked at 0.30 in the xl requirements by the
# runtime 0.45 / catalog 0.14 / transpiler 0.18 consistency set, so there
# is no installable pyarrow that both clears the CVE and satisfies the
# pinned ecosystem. The flaw is a DoS that requires processing a malicious
# Arrow/Parquet payload (no network exposure in these notebooks); pyarrow
# is not used directly by anything we ship.
#
# Drop this entry once qiskit-serverless relaxes its pyarrow<22 cap to
# admit >=23.0.1 (track upstream), or if the xl serverless pin moves off
# the 0.30 line to a release that does.
CVE-2026-25087

# GHSA-36hh-v3qg-5jq4 - pyo3 out-of-bounds read in nth/nth_back for
# PyList/PyTuple iterators (HIGH; fixed in 0.29.0).
#
# pyo3 is a Rust<->Python binding crate compiled *into* other packages'
# native wheels in the base image's conda environment (e.g. cryptography
# and friends); it is not a pip-installable package we pin or can
# `pip upgrade` directly — the fix only arrives when those upstream
# wheels rebuild against pyo3 0.29. It came in with the base bump to
# 9388739d, which on balance is a big win: that digest cleared the
# libssl, jupyter-server, PyJWT, tornado and cryptography findings AND
# the rust-openssl/AWS-LC RCE set (CVE-2026-42327) that blocked the
# earlier e9bea43 (#83) and 0b358e9e (#87) bumps. The flaw is an OOB
# *read* (info-disclosure/crash), not RCE, reachable only via in-process
# Python iterating a maliciously-constructed native sequence.
#
# Drop this once the base image's wheels rebuild against pyo3 >=0.29.0.
GHSA-36hh-v3qg-5jq4

# CVE-2026-54512 / CVE-2026-54513 - jackson-databind unsafe-polymorphic
# deserialization gadgets (both HIGH; PolymorphicTypeValidator bypass and
# array-subtype allowlist bypass respectively; fixed in 2.18.8/2.21.4/3.1.4).
#
# The flagged jackson-databind 2.18.6 is a Java jar vendored *inside* Ray's
# distribution jar at
#   opt/conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/ray/jars/ray_dist.jar
# Ray is pulled into every -xl/-xxl flavor transitively via qiskit-serverless
# (pinned ~=0.30 in the xl requirements). jackson is not a pip-installable
# package we can `pip upgrade` — it ships bundled in ray_dist.jar, so the fix
# only arrives when Ray rebundles a patched jackson. Only xl/xxl carry Ray;
# the -small flavors don't, which is why they keep passing. Both CVEs are
# exploitable only when attacker-controlled JSON is deserialized with default
# typing / unsafe polymorphic handling enabled — not something these notebooks
# expose; nothing we ship drives Ray's JVM deserialization on untrusted input.
#
# Drop these once Ray rebundles jackson-databind >=2.18.8 (track upstream Ray
# releases), or if the xl serverless pin moves to a Ray that already has it.
CVE-2026-54512
CVE-2026-54513

# GHSA-r7wm-3cxj-wff9 - jackson-core async-parser maxNumberLength bypass
# (HIGH; a crafted JSON number can exceed the configured length limit in the
# non-blocking/async parser, a DoS; fixed in 2.18.8/2.21.4/2.22.1).
#
# Same situation and same jar as the jackson-databind pair above: the flagged
# jackson-core 2.18.6 is vendored *inside* Ray's ray_dist.jar (xl/xxl only, via
# qiskit-serverless ~=0.30); not pip-upgradable, so the fix only lands when Ray
# rebundles a patched jackson. Entered Trivy's DB between the 07-21 (green) and
# 07-22 (red) nightly runs, alongside the base-layer jupyterlab XSS advisories
# fixed in-image on the Dockerfile pip line. The async streaming parser this
# affects is not driven on untrusted input by anything these notebooks ship.
#
# Drop once Ray rebundles jackson-core >=2.18.8 (track upstream Ray releases),
# or if the xl serverless pin moves to a Ray that already has it.
GHSA-r7wm-3cxj-wff9
